# Clean Architecture Rules

## Presentation Layer

Responsibilities:
- UI rendering
- navigation
- local UI state
- interactions
- loading/error states
- haptic/sound feedback triggers

Allowed:
- providers / StateNotifiers
- widgets
- formatting
- navigation logic
- `FeedbackService` calls

Forbidden:
- `SharedPreferences` calls
- datasource access
- business rules
- serialization
- persistence logic

---

## Domain Layer

Responsibilities:
- entities
- business rules
- use cases
- repository contracts

Requirements:
- framework-independent
- highly testable
- pure business logic

Forbidden:
- Flutter imports
- `shared_preferences` imports
- platform service imports
- UI logic

---

## Data Layer

Responsibilities:
- repository implementations
- datasource integrations
- models (`TaskModel`, etc.)
- JSON serialization

Forbidden:
- widget dependencies
- presentation logic

---

# Riverpod Engineering Rules

Use:
- `Provider` for DI and use case injection
- `StateNotifierProvider` for mutable feature state (tasks, XP, settings)

Validate:
- provider boundaries
- `sharedPreferencesProvider` override in `main.dart`
- dependency flow
- async state consistency

Prefer:
- feature-scoped providers
- isolated state
- predictable state transitions
- `select()` optimization
- persistence through use cases (`SaveTasks`, `SaveXp`)

Avoid:
- global mutable state
- provider over-coupling
- circular dependencies
- oversized providers
- provider side effects bypassing use cases

---

# Flutter Engineering Rules

Prefer:
- widget composition
- small reusable widgets
- `const` constructors
- extracted UI sections
- `Theme.of(context).colorScheme` for colors
- `AppAnimations` for durations/curves
- bottom sheets with `BorderRadius.vertical(top: Radius.circular(28))`
- cards with `BorderRadius.circular(24)`, `elevation: 0`

Implement:
- loading states
- error states
- empty states
- responsive layouts
- accessibility basics
- dispose controllers (confetti, animation, timers)

Avoid:
- massive widgets
- business rules in widgets
- expensive `build()` operations
- deeply nested widgets
- duplicated UI logic
- magic animation numbers

---

# Local Persistence Engineering Rules

All persistence must go through:
Provider/StateNotifier → UseCase → Repository → DataSource → SharedPreferences

Never:
- access `SharedPreferences` directly from UI or domain
- serialize in widgets
- expose datasource implementation to presentation

Validate:
- JSON encode/decode safety
- corrupt data recovery
- key naming consistency
- save timing (avoid excessive writes)

Future remote sync readiness requires:
- datasource isolation
- repository abstraction
- centralized serialization
- transport-independent entities

---

# Platform Services Engineering Rules

Platform services live in `lib/core/services/` as singletons:
- `NotificationService`
- `LiveActivityService` (iOS)
- `ForegroundService` (Android)
- `FeedbackService`

Rules:
- initialize in `main.dart` before `runApp`
- start/update/stop from presentation layer only
- always clean up on timer complete, dialog dismiss, or dispose
- request permissions at startup
- respect `settingsNotifierProvider` for sound/haptic toggles

---

# Security Engineering Rules

Validate:
- input validation on user content
- safe JSON parsing
- no secrets in code
- platform permissions justified

Never:
- hardcode secrets
- expose sensitive logs
- persist unvalidated user input

---

# Performance Engineering Rules

## Flutter Performance

Optimize:
- rebuild frequency
- widget tree complexity
- animation controller lifecycle
- navigation performance
- startup overhead

Review:
- expensive synchronous work in `build()`
- nested async builders
- unnecessary renders

---

## Persistence Performance

Optimize:
- save frequency
- startup load (async init pattern from `HomeScreen`)
- JSON payload size

Avoid:
- saving full state on every trivial UI event
- blocking UI on persistence

---

# Error Handling Rules

Every async flow must handle:
- loading
- success
- empty
- failure
- corrupt/missing data recovery

Never:
- swallow exceptions silently
- expose raw exceptions to users
- ignore fallback behavior

Provide:
- actionable user messages
- graceful defaults (empty list, zero XP)
- recovery strategy

---

# Offline & Resilience Rules

The app is local-first — validate:
- data survives app restart
- state recovery on startup
- no data loss on rapid interactions
- timer state vs persisted task state consistency

---

